MF=10
MT= 16 - (n,2n) cross section
Reaction (n,2n) on Al-27 leads to production Al-26 in ground
and metastable states.  The 228.305 keV metastable level (J= 0+)
and  ground level (J= 5+) undergoes 100% via e-capture decay mode
with a half-life of (6.3452+-0.0019) seconds and  (717000+-24000)
years, respectively [1].
Microscopic experimental data for Al-27(n,2n)Al-26m reaction
excitation function is given in works [2-7]  and  covered neutron
energies range from 13.94 to 20.2 MeV.
Experimental data of of works [4-7] in the prosess of analy-
sis were corrected to the new standards for relevant monitor reac-
tions and recommended decay data for Al-26m [1]. Special correcti-
on was applied to the experimental data of Mani et al. [2]. These
experimental data  were renormalized to the results  of corrected
measurements of Arnold and Rayburn [4]  in the overlapping energy
range 16.20 - 17.98 MeV. Applied correction factor was was equal
Microscopic experimental data for Al-27(n,2n)Al-26g reaction
excitation function is given in works [8-16] and covered neutron
energies range from 13.67 to 33.6 MeV.
The Al-27(n,2n)Al-26g reaction cross section given in works
[8-10], [12] and [14] were measured by traditional activation me-
thod. Cross section presented in works [11], [13], [15] and [16]
had been measured by accelerator mass spectrometry (AMS) method.
Experimental data of works [9-10], [12-16] in the process of
analysis  were corrected to  the new standards  for  the relevant
monitor reactions and recommended decay data for Al-26g [1].
Special correction  was applied to the experimental  data of
works [9], [11] and [12]. Experimental data of Iwasaki et al. [9]
after correction to the new standards were renormalized to the in-
tegral of Wallner et al. data [16] in overlapping interval 14.08 -
14.68 MeV, Fc= 0.61767.  Determined by  AMS  method  experimental
data of Nakamura et al. [11] were renormalized to the integral of
Wallner et al. data [16] in overlapping interval 15.30-19.00 MeV,
Fc= 1.27217.  Corrected to the new standards experimental data of
Ikeda et al. [12] were  renormalized to a value  (29.50+-2.00) mb
at 14.80 MeV, determined by AMS method in JAERI activation [16].
Evaluation of the  Al-27(n,2n)Al-26m  and  Al-27(n,2n)Al-26g
reaction excitation functions in the energy region from threshold
to 60 MeV  was carried out  by means of  statistical analysis  of
cross sections from prepared data bases.
Data base for the  Al-27(n,2n)Al-26m  reaction was included
the analyzed experimental data [2-7]  and renormalized data from
EAF-2010, TENDL-2014 libraries and GNASH calculation.  Cross sec-
tions from the last three sources were renormalized to the experi-
mental data at 20 MeV.
Data base for the  Al-27(n,2n)Al-26g  reaction was included
the analyzed experimental data  [8-9], [11-12] and [15-16].  Data
from  EAF-2010, TENDL-2014 libraries  and  GNASH calculation were
used also in the evaluation above 20 MeV. The EAF-2010,TENDL-2014
and  GNASH data were renormalized at  20 MeV for the experimental
data. Experimental data  from works [10], [13] were  rejected due
to inconsistency with the main bulk of measured cross sections.
Data given in Ref.[14] was not taken into account also.Authors of
work [14] consider that  the final results of their investigation
are presented in the Ref. [16].
Statistical analysis  of cross sections  from both data bases
was carried out by means of PADE-2 code [17].  Rational function
was used as the model function [18].
Evaluated  Al-27(n,2n)Al-26g  and  Al-27(n,2n)Al-26m reaction
excitation functions are given in MF=10, MT=16 file.
MF=40

Al-27(n,2n)Al-26g reaction  are given  in the form  of a relative

MT=103 - (n,p) cross section
Microscopic experimental data  [1-77]  were  analyzed in  the
process of preparation  of input data base  for the evaluation of
cross sections  and  their uncertainty  for the  Al-27(n,p)Mg-27
reaction.  During this procedure all experimental data  if it was
possible were corrected to the new recommended cross section data
for monitor reactions used in the measurements and to the new re-
commended decay data from ref. [78].
Excitation function for the  Al-27(n,p)Mg-27 reaction in the
energy region from threshold to 23.0 MeV was evaluated by  means
of statistical analysis of experimental cross section data [1-59].
Special correction was done with experimental data [3], [8],
Experimental data of Hudson and Morgan [3], Gabbard et al.[8],
Ferguson and Albergotti [15] , Cuzzocrea et al. [17] , Csikai and
Chimoe et al. [47]  were renormalized  to the results  of precise
absolute measurements of Ikeda et al.[53] in the overlapping ener-
gy ranges. Correction factors for the experimental data [3], [8],
respectively.  Data  of independent  measurements  of Csikai  and
Chimoe et al. [47] were multiplied to the coefficients Fc=0.89370
and Fc=0.92320, respectively.
Experimental data of Calvi et al. [13] and Shimizu et al.[59]
were corrected  to the results  of Smith and Meadows measurements
with Li-7(p,n)Be-7 neutron source [27]  in the overlapping energy
intervals. Correction factors were Fc=0.96506 and Fc=0.74834, res-
pectively. On the first step of correction data of Shimizu et al.
were renormalized  to  the new evaluated  cross sections  for the
monitor reaction In-115(n,n')In-115m [79].
Cross sections for the  Al-27(n,p)Mg-27 reaction  measured by
Bass et al.[12] in the neutron energy range 6 - 9 MeV with 25 keV
step were renormalized to the integral of Smith and Meadows measu-
rements in the energy range 6.0 - 7.2 MeV.  Correction factor for
the experimental data [12] was Fc=0.81415 .
Data given in ref. [28] by Mostafa  were renormalized  to the
absolute cross section value for Al-27(n,p)Mg-27  reaction evalu-
ated at 7.1 MeV with taking into account  experimental data [12],
Experimental data [5], [8], [12] and [44] were used partially.
Data of Mani et al. [5]  were taken into account  only  for the 9
20.15 and 21.72 MeV. Renormalized experimental data of Gabbard et
al. [8] were used  only  for the 8 neutron energies: 12.90, 13.10,
tained from Bass et al. experiment [12] was taken into account in
the evaluation in the energy region 6.0 - 8.6 MeV.  In the energy
interval 8.6 - 9.0 MeV  this experiment gives significantly over-
estimated cross sections in a comparison with corrected experimen-
tal data [24], [27] and new experimental data [55]. Cross section
measured by Bradley et al. [44] for the neutron energy 11 MeV was
not input in the data base for evaluation  due to a very big dis-
crepancy with new experimental data of Csikai et al. [55].
Experimental cross section data [60-77] were rejected  due to
their discrepancy with the main bulk of experimental data [1-59].
In the rejected experiments [60-71] and [76-77] cross section
values were measured  only  in a one energy point in the interval
Statistical analysis of input cross section data  was carried
out by means of PADE-2 code [80].  Rational function  was used as
the model function [81].

were corrected to the new recommended cross sections [96] for the
monitor reactions.  Calculated and measured average cross-section

MF=3
MT=107 - (n,a) cross section
Microscopic experimental data  [1-72]  were  analyzed in  the
process of preparation  of input data base  for the evaluation of
cross sections  and  their uncertainty  for the  Al-27(n,p)Mg-27
reaction.  During this procedure all experimental data  if it was
possible were corrected to the new standards.
Special correction were also applied to the experimental data
[5], [9], [16], [19], [21], [33], and [43]. Cross section measured
by Tewes et al. for incident neutrons energies of  8.4-14 MeV [5]
were renormalized to the recent experimental data of Mannhart and
Schmidt [30]. The correction factor of Fc =1.36146 was determined
from the ratio of cross-section integrals in the overlapping ener-
gy interval 8.4-14 MeV.
The experimental data  of Tewes et al. [5], Gabbard and Kern
[9], Paulsen and Liskien [16], obtained in measurements with neut-
rons from T(d,n)He4 source  and  all experimental data of Menlove
et al. [21] were renormalized a factors Fc= 1.10138, Fc= 0.99177,
Fc=0.96830 and Fc=1.07669, respectively.  Correction factors were
determined from the ratio of cross-section integrals  of Ikeda et
al.[50] and Filatenkov and Chuvaev [54] to the adequate integrals
of these experimental data.
Data of Hemingway et al.[19] iand Welch et al. [33] were re-
normalized to a values of 110.6 mb at 14.8 MeV and 38.51 mb at 20
MeV, respectively.
The cross-sections ratio  of Mg24(n,p) to Al27(n,a) reactions
in the energy range 13.59-17.86 MeV  was measured by Janzyszyn et
al.[43]. The Al27(n,a)Na24 reaction cross sections from this expe-
rimental data were determined from the reverse ratios with using
data for Mg24(n,p)Na24 excitation function from Ref. [73]. Experi-
mental data of Janzyszyn et al. were obtained by means of Mg samp-
les with  the natural isotopic composition. Therefore, these data
were corrected also for the contribution  from  the Mg25(n,x)Na24
and Mg26(n,t)Na24 reactions. Cross-section data for these reacti-
ons were taken from Ref. [74].
Experimental data of Tsabaris for the alpha-production cross-
section on Al [52] were taken only for the incident neutron ener-
gies 6.28-, 8.0-, 9.0-MeV.  Data for 14.0 MeV point  could not be
qualified as the Al27(n,a)Na24 reaction cross section.
Experimental data of Coszach et al.[55] measurer above 21 MeV
was not taken into accout also.
Cross-section data from Refs. [57-71] was rejected completely
due to their discrepancy with the main bulk of experimental data.
Within these rejected experimental data, the cross-section values
reported in Refs. [57], [59-61] and [64-65] comprised only one or
two energy points in the interval 14 - 15 MeV.
Excitation function for the  Al-27(n,a)Na-24 reaction in the
energy region from threshold to 40.0 MeV was evaluated by  means
of statistical analysis of experimental cross-section data [1-56]
and data obtained from theoretical model calculations.
Statistical analysis of input cross section data  was carried
out by means of PADE-2 code [75].  Rational function  was used as
the model function [76].
Evaluated in the energy range 23.8-40.0 MeV excitation func-
tion is the sum of cross sections of the reactions: Al27(n,a)Na24,
Al27(n,p+t)Na24, Al27(n,n+He3)Na24, Al27(n,d+d)Na24, Al27(n,n+p+d)
Na24 and Al27(n,2n+2p)Na24.
Evaluated  Al-27(n,a+)Na-24 reaction excitation function  was
tested with using integral experimental data [77] for U-235 ther-
mal fission neutron spectrum [78] and  Cf-252 spontaneous fission
neutron spectrum [79]. Calculated and measured values of averaged
cross-section are given in the Table 1.
